`IFormFile` buffers into memory by default — for large files you need to read the raw request body stream instead.

**Key changes:**

1. **Disable the form body-size limit** and read from `Request.Body` (or use `Request.ReadFormAsync` with `MultipartBodyLengthLimit`):

```csharp
// Program.cs – ASP.NET Core 8 Minimal API

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise Kestrel's max request body size (default is ~28 MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024); // 2 GB

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Content-Type must be multipart/form-data
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");

    // Read the form while streaming file sections to disk
    var form = await request.ReadFormAsync(new FormOptions
    {
        MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024,
        BufferBody = false          // ← critical: do NOT buffer into RAM
    });

    var file = form.Files.FirstOrDefault();
    if (file is null || file.Length == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No file received.");

    var destPath = Path.Combine(Path.GetTempPath(), file.FileName);

    // Stream directly from the multipart section to disk
    await using var destStream = File.Create(destPath);
    await using var srcStream  = file.OpenReadStream();
    await srcStream.CopyToAsync(destStream);

    return Results.Ok(new { file.FileName, file.Length, destPath });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();

app.Run();
```

2. **If you need full manual control** (no `ReadFormAsync`), use `MultipartReader` directly — this gives you each section as a stream you drain yourself:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

app.MapPost("/upload-manual", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(
        MediaTypeHeaderValue.Parse(request.ContentType).Boundary).Value;

    var reader  = new MultipartReader(boundary!, request.Body);
    var section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();

    while (section is not null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) && cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            var fileName = cd.FileNameStar.Value ?? cd.FileName.Value;
            var destPath = Path.Combine(Path.GetTempPath(), fileName!);

            await using var dest = File.Create(destPath);
            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(dest);   // zero extra buffering

            return Results.Ok(new { fileName, destPath });
        }
        section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();
    }

    return Results.BadRequest("No file section found.");
}).DisableAntiforgery();
```

**Why this works:**

| | `IFormFile` (default) | `MultipartReader` / `BufferBody=false` |
|---|---|---|
| Memory | Entire file buffered in RAM | Only small read buffer (~80 KB) |
| 2 GB file | OOM crash | Streams to disk, constant memory |

**Checklist:**
- Set `Kestrel MaxRequestBodySize` ≥ your limit (default ≈ 28 MB)
- Set `FormOptions.MultipartBodyLengthLimit` to match
- Set `BufferBody = false` (or use `MultipartReader` directly)
- If behind a reverse proxy (nginx/IIS), raise its limit too (`client_max_body_size` / `maxAllowedContentLength`)
